Analysis and Forecasting of CDC Weekly Disease Surveillance Data

Project Description

This project provides a comprehensive exploratory and predictive analysis of weekly disease surveillance data from the CDCs National Notifiable Diseases Surveillance System (NNDSS). Using the dataset extracted on September 24, 2025, the project demonstrates Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA), forecasting, and visualization techniques applied to public health data. Key outcomes include identification of trends, anomalies, seasonality patterns, and preparation of structured outputs for reporting or dashboards.

Project Objectives

  1. Data Preparation & Cleaning
  • Standardize and clean CDC NNDSS weekly data for analysis.
  • Handle missing values, duplicates, inconsistent formats, and convert MMWR year/week to datetime.
  1. Feature Engineering
  • Aggregate weekly cases at the national level by disease (Label).
  • Generate lag features, week-over-week growth rates, contribution to cumulative YTD, and flags for exceeding 52-week maxima.
  1. Data Analysis

  • Visualize temporal trends, seasonality, and cumulative counts for diseases.

  • Identify peak weeks, trends across years, and variations between diseases.

  1. Forecasting & Benchmarking

  • Apply and compare multiple time series models (SARIMA, Exponential Smoothing, machine learning models) for short-term forecasting.

  • Evaluate model performance using MAPE and RMSE.

  • Forecast future weekly disease cases for top diseases.

  1. Visualization & Reporting

  • Generate heatmaps, stacked area charts, geospatial hotspot maps, and other visualizations.

  • Prepare a clean dashboard-ready dataset summarizing key metrics, trends, and flags.

Data Collection & Dataset

  • Source: CDCs National Notifiable Diseases Surveillance System (NNDSS) weekly data, latest update on September 24, 2025.

https://data.cdc.gov/NNDSS/NNDSS-Weekly-Data/x9gk-5huc/data_preview

  • Fields: Current week, Previous 52 week Max, Cumulative YTD Current MMWR Year, Cumulative YTD Previous MMWR Year, Label (disease name), Reporting Area, MMWR year/week, optional lat/lon for geospatial mapping.

# -------------------------
# Data Cleaning & Preprocessing
# -------------------------

# Convert numeric columns

numeric_cols = [
    "Current week",
    "Previous 52 week Max",
    "Cumulative YTD Current MMWR Year",
    "Cumulative YTD Previous MMWR Year",
    "MMWR Week",
    "MMWR Year"
]

for col in numeric_cols:
    if col in df.columns:
        df[col] = (
            df[col]
            .astype(str)
            .str.replace(",", "", regex=False)        # remove thousand separators
            .str.replace(r"[^\d.-]", "", regex=True)  # remove CDC special markers
        )
        df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors="coerce")

# Strip whitespace for consistency in string columns
for col in df.select_dtypes(include='object').columns:
    df[col] = df[col].str.strip()

# Parse geocodes
if 'geocode' in df.columns:
    def parse_point(point_str):
        try:
            lon, lat = map(float, str(point_str).replace('POINT (','').replace(')','').split())
            return lat, lon
        except:
            return np.nan, np.nan

    latlon = df['geocode'].apply(parse_point)
    df['lat'] = latlon.apply(lambda t: t[0])
    df['lon'] = latlon.apply(lambda t: t[1])
else:
    df['lat'] = np.nan
    df['lon'] = np.nan

# Remove duplicate rows
before = len(df)
df = df.drop_duplicates().reset_index(drop=True)
after = len(df)
print(f"Removed {before - after} duplicate rows. Remaining: {after}")

# Filter weekly case values
df_clean = df[df['Current week'].notna()].copy()
print(f"Cleaned dataset ready for analysis: {len(df_clean)} rows with reported weekly cases.")

# Missing values
missing_pct = (df_clean.isnull().sum() / len(df_clean) * 100).sort_values(ascending=False)
print("\n% Missing Values (Top 10 Columns):")
display(missing_pct.head(10))

# Summary statistics for numeric fields
existing_numeric = [col for col in numeric_cols if col in df_clean.columns]
print("\nSummary Statistics for Numeric Columns:")
display(df_clean[existing_numeric].describe())

Missing values in the NNDSS weekly dataset are expected because of how public health surveillance works in the United States.

  • Not every disease is legally reportable in every jurisdiction, so many states do not submit counts at all for certain conditions these appear as blank cells rather than zeros. Even when a disease is reportable, jurisdictions often skip weeks, revise earlier data, or delay submissions, which naturally produces gaps in weekly counts.

  • Some fields such as Previous 52 week Max or cumulative year-to-date totalscan only be calculated after enough historical data exists, so they remain empty for newer conditions or early in the year.

  • LOCATION2 and geocodes are optional fields and are often omitted entirely by states.

Because these gaps reflect policy, reporting practices, and the structure of the surveillance system not data corruption this level of missingness is acceptable and expected. The key is to analyze the data with this context in mind, filtering by disease, jurisdiction, and time period rather than assuming all fields apply everywhere.

Next step is to prepare our dataset for analysis by parsing to ensure our fields are of the correct data types

# Ensure consistent naming
df_clean = df_clean.rename(columns={
    "Current MMWR Year": "MMWR Year",
    "MMWR WEEK": "MMWR Week"
}) if "Current MMWR Year" in df_clean.columns else df_clean

# Ensure year/week are numeric so we can create date variable
df_clean["MMWR Year"] = pd.to_numeric(df_clean["MMWR Year"], errors="coerce")
df_clean["MMWR Week"] = pd.to_numeric(df_clean["MMWR Week"], errors="coerce")

# Build an ISO week string like "2024-W05-1" Using Monday as the anchor point for each epidemiological week
iso_strings = (
    df_clean["MMWR Year"].astype("Int64").astype(str)
    + "-W"
    + df_clean["MMWR Week"].astype("Int64").astype(str).str.zfill(2)
    + "-1"  # Monday anchor
)

# Convert ISO week string  actual timestamp
df_clean["date"] = pd.to_datetime(
    iso_strings,
    format="%G-W%V-%u",
    errors="coerce"
)

# Quick check
print("Date range:", df_clean["date"].min(), "to", df_clean["date"].max())
display(df_clean[["MMWR Year", "MMWR Week", "date"]].head())

MMWR weeks (used by CDC) dont always line up with standard calendar weeks, so converting MMWR Year + MMWR WEEK a proper date is essential for time-series analysis, forecasting, visualization, and trend comparison. To do this correctly, we rely on ISO week formatting, which matches how CDC structures epidemiological weeks.

Feature Engineering

This section transforms raw NNDSS weekly data into a format suitable for analysis, visualization, and forecasting. Aggregating to the national level per disease clarifies trends, seasonality, anomalies, and growth patterns.

In[6]:
# -------------------------
# Feature Engineering
# -------------------------

CURRENT = 'Current week'
MAX52   = 'Previous 52 week Max'
CUMYTD  = 'Cumulative YTD Current MMWR Year'

# Aggregate to national-level weekly series per disease
agg = (
    df_clean.groupby(['Label', 'date'], as_index=False)
            [[CURRENT, MAX52, CUMYTD]]
            .sum()
            .sort_values(['Label', 'date'])
            .reset_index(drop=True)
)

# Insert missing weeks per disease
full_series = []
for disease, temp in agg.groupby('Label'):
    full_range = pd.DataFrame({
        'date': pd.date_range(temp['date'].min(), temp['date'].max(), freq='W-MON')
    })
    merged = full_range.merge(temp, on='date', how='left')
    merged['Label'] = disease
    merged[[CURRENT, MAX52, CUMYTD]] = merged[[CURRENT, MAX52, CUMYTD]].fillna(0)
    full_series.append(merged)

agg = pd.concat(full_series, ignore_index=True).sort_values(['Label', 'date'])

# Lag features (14 week lags)
for lag in range(1, 5):
    agg[f'lag_{lag}'] = agg.groupby('Label')[CURRENT].shift(lag).fillna(0)

# Week-over-week growth rate
agg['growth_rate'] = agg.groupby('Label')[CURRENT].pct_change()

# Contribution to year-to-date (%)
agg['pct_of_ytd'] = agg[CURRENT] / agg[CUMYTD].replace(0, np.nan)

# 3-week & 8-week rolling averages
agg['roll3'] = agg.groupby('Label')[CURRENT].rolling(3, min_periods=1).mean().reset_index(level=0, drop=True)
agg['roll8'] = agg.groupby('Label')[CURRENT].rolling(8, min_periods=1).mean().reset_index(level=0, drop=True)

# Epidemiological week features
agg['weekofyear'] = agg['date'].dt.isocalendar().week.astype(int)
agg['year']       = agg['date'].dt.year.astype(int)

# Flag very-rare diseases (will be excluded from forecasting)
disease_stats = (
    agg.groupby('Label')[CURRENT]
       .agg(['sum', lambda x: (x > 0).sum()])
       .rename(columns={'<lambda_0>': 'non_zero_weeks'})
)

rare_diseases = disease_stats[
    (disease_stats['sum'] < 100) |
    (disease_stats['non_zero_weeks'] < 30)
].index.tolist()

agg['is_rare'] = agg['Label'].isin(rare_diseases)

# Quick Check
print(f"Identified {len(rare_diseases)} rare diseases (flagged for exclusion in forecasting).")
display(agg.head())

# ============================================
# Analysis 1: Forecast Weekly Cases
# ============================================

from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_percentage_error, mean_squared_error
from statsmodels.tsa.holtwinters import ExponentialSmoothing
from statsmodels.tsa.statespace.sarimax import SARIMAX
import lightgbm as lgb
import xgboost as xgb
import warnings
from statsmodels.tools.sm_exceptions import ValueWarning

weekly_col = "Current week"

# Identify top 5 high-volume diseases
if "top5_labels" not in globals():
    top5_labels = (
        agg.groupby("Label")[weekly_col]
           .sum()
           .sort_values(ascending=False)
           .head(5)
           .index
           .tolist()
    )
print("Top 5 Labels:", top5_labels)


# Metrics function
def compute_metrics(y_true, y_pred):
    """Return MAPE, RMSE, and accuracy."""
    mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_true, y_pred)
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred))
    accuracy = 100 * (1 - mape)
    return mape, rmse, accuracy

# Additional features and functions for forecasting
def add_ml_features(df):
    """Add lag, rolling, and seasonal features for ML models."""
    df = df.copy()
    for lag in range(1, 5):
        if f"lag_{lag}" not in df.columns:
            df[f"lag_{lag}"] = df["y"].shift(lag)

    df["roll_3w"] = df["roll3"] if "roll3" in df.columns else df["y"].rolling(3).mean()
    df["roll_8w"] = df["roll8"] if "roll8" in df.columns else df["y"].rolling(8).mean()

    df["week_of_year"] = df["weekofyear"] if "weekofyear" in df.columns else df["ds"].dt.isocalendar().week
    if "year" not in df.columns:
        df["year"] = df["ds"].dt.year

    return df

def fit_forecasts(series, forecast_horizon=52):
    """Fit SARIMA, ETS, LightGBM, and XGBoost forecasts."""
    results = {}
    ts = series["y"].astype(float)
    ts.index = series["ds"]

    # SARIMA
    try:
        sarima = SARIMAX(
            ts,
            order=(1, 1, 1),
            seasonal_order=(1, 1, 1, 52),
            enforce_stationarity=False,
            enforce_invertibility=False,
        ).fit(disp=False)

        sarima_fc = sarima.get_forecast(steps=forecast_horizon).predicted_mean
        metrics = compute_metrics(ts[-forecast_horizon:], sarima_fc) if len(ts) >= forecast_horizon else (np.nan, np.nan, np.nan)

        results["SARIMA"] = {
            "Model": sarima,
            "Forecast": sarima_fc,
            "MAPE": metrics[0],
            "RMSE": metrics[1],
            "Forecast Accuracy (%)": metrics[2],
            "Details": {"order": (1, 1, 1), "seasonal_order": (1, 1, 1, 52)}
        }
    except Exception as e:
        results["SARIMA"] = {"Forecast": None, "Details": str(e)}

    # Exponential Smoothing (ETS)
    try:
        ets = ExponentialSmoothing(ts, trend="add", seasonal="add", seasonal_periods=52).fit()
        ets_fc = ets.forecast(forecast_horizon)
        metrics = compute_metrics(ts[-forecast_horizon:], ets_fc) if len(ts) >= forecast_horizon else (np.nan, np.nan, np.nan)

        results["ETS"] = {
            "Model": ets,
            "Forecast": ets_fc,
            "MAPE": metrics[0],
            "RMSE": metrics[1],
            "Forecast Accuracy (%)": metrics[2],
            "Details": {"trend": "add", "seasonal": "add", "period": 52}
        }
    except Exception as e:
        results["ETS"] = {"Forecast": None, "Details": str(e)}

    # ML Models
    try:
        df_ml = add_ml_features(series).dropna()
        if len(df_ml) > 20:
            features = ["lag_1","lag_2","lag_3","lag_4","roll_3w","roll_8w","week_of_year","year"]
            X = df_ml[features]
            y = df_ml["y"]

            train_X, test_X = X[:-forecast_horizon], X[-forecast_horizon:]
            train_y, test_y = y[:-forecast_horizon], y[-forecast_horizon:]

            forecast_index = pd.date_range(start=series["ds"].iloc[-1]+pd.Timedelta(weeks=1),
                                           periods=forecast_horizon, freq="W-MON")

            # LightGBM
            lgb_model = lgb.LGBMRegressor(verbose=-1)
            lgb_model.fit(train_X, train_y)
            lgb_pred = pd.Series(lgb_model.predict(test_X), index=forecast_index[:len(test_y)])
            mape, rmse, acc = compute_metrics(test_y.values, lgb_pred)
            results["LightGBM"] = {"Model": lgb_model, "Forecast": lgb_pred, "MAPE": mape, "RMSE": rmse, "Forecast Accuracy (%)": acc, "Details": {"Features": features}}

            # XGBoost
            xgb_model = xgb.XGBRegressor(objective="reg:squarederror", verbosity=0)
            xgb_model.fit(train_X, train_y)
            xgb_pred = pd.Series(xgb_model.predict(test_X), index=forecast_index[:len(test_y)])
            mape, rmse, acc = compute_metrics(test_y.values, xgb_pred)
            results["XGBoost"] = {"Model": xgb_model, "Forecast": xgb_pred, "MAPE": mape, "RMSE": rmse, "Forecast Accuracy (%)": acc, "Details": {"Features": features}}

    except Exception as e:
        results["ML"] = {"Forecast": None, "Details": str(e)}

    return results

# Run forecast models
summary_rows = []

for label in top5_labels:
    series = agg[agg["Label"]==label][["date", weekly_col]].rename(columns={"date":"ds", weekly_col:"y"}).reset_index(drop=True)

    if len(series) < 30:
        continue

    series = series.set_index("ds").asfreq("W-MON").reset_index()
    with warnings.catch_warnings():
        warnings.simplefilter("ignore", category=ValueWarning)
        results = fit_forecasts(series, forecast_horizon=52)

    valid = {name:r for name,r in results.items() if r["Forecast"] is not None}
    best_model = min(valid.items(), key=lambda x: x[1]["RMSE"])[0] if valid else None
    best_forecast = valid[best_model]["Forecast"] if valid else None

  # Plot actual vs forecast
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,4))
    plt.plot(series["ds"], series["y"], marker="o", label="Actual")
    if best_forecast is not None:
        plt.plot(best_forecast.index, best_forecast.values, marker="x", label=f"Forecast ({best_model})")
    plt.title(f"{label}: Observed vs Forecasted Weekly Counts")
    plt.xlabel("Date")
    plt.ylabel("Cases")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

  # Summary metrics
    for model_name, metrics in results.items():
        summary_rows.append({
            "Label": label,
            "Model": model_name,
            "MAPE": metrics.get("MAPE"),
            "RMSE": metrics.get("RMSE"),
            "Forecast Accuracy (%)": metrics.get("Forecast Accuracy (%)"),
            "Model Details": metrics.get("Details")
        })

# Forecast summary table
summary_df = pd.DataFrame(summary_rows)[["Label","Model","MAPE","RMSE","Forecast Accuracy (%)","Model Details"]]
print("\nForecast Summary:")
display(summary_df.sort_values(["Label","RMSE"]))

To forecast weekly disease cases for the 5 most common diseases, 4 forecasting models were fitted to the processed dataset.

  • Seasonal ARIMA - captures trends, autocorrelation, and repeating seasonal patterns, making it ideal for diseases with clear yearly cycles.
  • Exponential Smoothing - focuses on smoothing past observations and modeling trend and seasonality directly, performing best on stable, less noisy time series.
  • LightGBM - uses fast, leaf-wise boosted decision trees that excel on large datasets with many engineered features. It is best when you need very fast training and strong performance on nonlinear, noisy patterns.
  • XGBoost - uses a more conservative level-wise boosting strategy with strong regularization, making it stable and highly accurate on structured, medium-sized datasets. Its best when you want reliable generalization and strong performance on nonlinear time-series relationships.

The models are evaluated and compared with their RMSE, MAPE, and Forecast Accuracy for each of the model. The best model is then selected as the one with the lowest RMSE.

The line graph shows the 12 week forecast using the best model

Interpretation:

  • The 5 most common diseases in the US are Campylobacteriosis, Chlamydia trachomatis infection, Gonorrhea, Hepatitis C, and Salmonellosis.
  • Across the five diseases, tree-based machine learning models (LightGBM and XGBoost) consistently outperform classical time-series models (SARIMA and ETS)
  • Diseases with stable weekly reporting behavior (Chlamydia, Gonorrhea) yield highly reliable predictions - thus we need to encourage consistent reporting across the country.
  • Foodborne illnesses show seasonal patterns.
  • Chronic diseases like Hepatitis C are less predictable.

Actionable Insights:

  • Seasonal gastrointestinal diseases need proactive resource planning - Increase food-safety inspections and public health messaging before peak seasons and Prepare hospitals/labs for higher case loads during expected surge weeks.
  • STIs (Chlamydia & Gonorrhea) have predictable trends, enabling stable service planning
  • Machine learning models outperform classical time series for most diseases - Integrate ML-based forecasting pipelines into routine surveillance dashboards and weekly monitoring.
  • Because XGBoost/LightGBM achieve highly accurate predictions, deviations between forecasted vs. observed values can act as early warnings.

# Analysis 2: YTD Cumulative Cases Comparison with Surge Detection
# ==========================================

weekly_col = 'Current week'  # weekly cases
col_year   = 'year'
col_date   = 'date'
df = agg.copy()

# Yearly YTD summary
years = sorted(df[col_year].unique())
current_ytd_list = []
prev_ytd_list = []
start_dates = []
end_dates = []

for yr in years:
    df_cur = df[df[col_year] == yr].sort_values(col_date)
    start_date, end_date = df_cur[col_date].min(), df_cur[col_date].max()
    start_dates.append(start_date)
    end_dates.append(end_date)

    # Current YTD
    current_ytd = df_cur[weekly_col].sum()
    current_ytd_list.append(current_ytd)

    # Previous-year YTD for same period
    prev_year = yr - 1
    df_prev = df[(df[col_year] == prev_year) &
                 (df[col_date] >= start_date.replace(year=prev_year)) &
                 (df[col_date] <= end_date.replace(year=prev_year))]
    prev_ytd = df_prev[weekly_col].sum()
    prev_ytd_list.append(prev_ytd)

df_yearly = pd.DataFrame({
    'Year': years,
    'Current_YTD': current_ytd_list,
    'Previous_YTD': prev_ytd_list,
    'Start_Date': start_dates,
    'End_Date': end_dates
})

# % change from previous year
df_yearly["Pct_Change (%)"] = ((df_yearly["Current_YTD"] - df_yearly["Previous_YTD"]) /
                               df_yearly["Previous_YTD"] * 100).round(1)
df_yearly["Pct_Change (%)"] = df_yearly["Pct_Change (%)"].replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan)

# Surge classification
def classify_change(pct):
    if pd.isna(pct):
        return "No Previous Year"
    if pct > 50:
        return "Severe Surge"
    elif pct > 20:
        return "Moderate Surge"
    elif pct > 0:
        return "Slight Increase"
    elif pct < -20:
        return "Large Decrease"
    else:
        return "Stable / Mild Change"

df_yearly["Surge_Category"] = df_yearly["Pct_Change (%)"].apply(classify_change)

# Yearly YTD bar chart
x = np.arange(len(df_yearly))
width = 0.35
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(11, 5))
prev_bars = ax.bar(x - width/2, df_yearly["Previous_YTD"], width, label="Previous YTD")
curr_bars = ax.bar(x + width/2, df_yearly["Current_YTD"], width, label="Current YTD")

for i, (b1, b2, pct) in enumerate(zip(prev_bars, curr_bars, df_yearly["Pct_Change (%)"])):
    ax.text(b1.get_x() + b1.get_width()/2, b1.get_height(), f"{int(b1.get_height())}",
            ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=8)
    label_pct = f"({pct}%)" if not pd.isna(pct) else "(N/A)"
    ax.text(b2.get_x() + b2.get_width()/2, b2.get_height(), f"{int(b2.get_height())}\n{label_pct}",
            ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=8)

ax.set_xticks(x)
ax.set_xticklabels(df_yearly['Year'].astype(str))
ax.set_title("Cumulative YTD: Previous vs Current MMWR Year (Same Period)")
ax.set_ylabel("Total Cumulative Cases")
ax.legend()
ax.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.3)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Display yearly summary table with % change
print(" Yearly YTD Summary with % Change:")
display(df_yearly)

# Monthly Cases Comparison per Year
df['month_num'] = df[col_date].dt.month
monthly = df.groupby([col_year, 'month_num'])[weekly_col].sum().reset_index()
years = monthly[col_year].unique()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))
for yr in sorted(years):
    df_plot = monthly[monthly[col_year] == yr]
    ax.plot(df_plot['month_num'], df_plot[weekly_col], marker='o', label=str(yr))

ax.set_xticks(range(1, 13))
ax.set_xticklabels(['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun',
                    'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec'])
ax.set_title("Monthly Cases by Year")
ax.set_ylabel("Cases in Month")
ax.set_xlabel("Month")
ax.legend(title="Year")
ax.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.3)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Summary table: total cases per year
summary_total = df.groupby(col_year)[weekly_col].sum().reset_index()
summary_total = summary_total.rename(columns={weekly_col: 'Total_Cases'})

# Add % change column
summary_total['Pct_Change (%)'] = summary_total['Total_Cases'].pct_change() * 100

display(summary_total)

# ==========================================
# Analysis 3: Seasonality & Peak Week Analysis
# ==========================================

from scipy.signal import find_peaks

weekly_col = 'Current week'
label_col  = 'Label'
date_col   = 'date'

# Validation
for col in [weekly_col, label_col, date_col]:
    if col not in agg.columns:
        raise ValueError(f"Missing required column: {col}")

if not np.issubdtype(agg[date_col].dtype, np.datetime64):
    raise TypeError("Column 'date' must be datetime.")

# Extract ISO week and year
agg["iso_week"] = agg[date_col].dt.isocalendar().week.astype(int)
agg["iso_year"] = agg[date_col].dt.isocalendar().year.astype(int)

# Select Top 20 Diseases
top20 = agg.groupby(label_col)[weekly_col].sum().nlargest(20).index

# Median Seasonal Curve
season = (
    agg[agg[label_col].isin(top20)]
    .groupby([label_col, "iso_week"])[weekly_col]
    .median()
    .unstack(fill_value=0)
)

season = season.reindex(columns=range(1, 54), fill_value=0)
season_smooth = season.rolling(7, center=True, min_periods=1, axis=1).mean()

# Peak Week Detection
peak_week = season_smooth.idxmax(axis=1)
peak_value = season_smooth.max(axis=1)

secondary_peaks = {}
for disease in season_smooth.index:
    series = season_smooth.loc[disease].values
    peaks, _ = find_peaks(series, distance=4, height=np.percentile(series, 60))
    sec = [p+1 for p in peaks if p+1 != peak_week[disease]]  # skip primary peak
    secondary_peaks[disease] = sec if sec else None

# 3. Seasonality Strength
median_val = season_smooth.median(axis=1).replace(0, np.nan)
amplitude = ((season_smooth.max(axis=1) - season_smooth.min(axis=1)) / median_val).fillna(0)

def classify_seasonality(a):
    if a >= 1.5: return "Strong"
    if a >= 0.7: return "Moderate"
    if a >= 0.3: return "Weak"
    return "None"

seasonality_strength = amplitude.apply(classify_seasonality)

# Summary Table
summary = pd.DataFrame({
    "Peak_Week": peak_week,
    "Peak_Value": peak_value.round(1),
    "Secondary_Peaks": secondary_peaks,
    "Amplitude": amplitude.round(2),
    "Seasonality_Strength": seasonality_strength
}).loc[top20]

print("Peak & Seasonality Summary")
display(summary)

# Multiple seasonal curves
n_cols = 4
n_rows = int(np.ceil(len(top20)/n_cols))
fig, axes = plt.subplots(n_rows, n_cols, figsize=(18, n_rows*3), sharex=True, sharey=True)
axes = axes.flatten()

for i, disease in enumerate(top20):
    axes[i].plot(season_smooth.columns, season_smooth.loc[disease], marker='o')
    axes[i].set_title(disease)
    axes[i].axvline(peak_week[disease], color='red', linestyle='--', alpha=0.6)
    axes[i].grid(alpha=0.2)

for j in range(i+1, len(axes)):
    fig.delaxes(axes[j])

fig.suptitle("Seasonal Curves with Primary Peak Weeks (Top 20 Diseases)", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("ISO Week")
plt.ylabel("Median Weekly Cases")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Peak Week Dot Calendar
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
for idx, disease in enumerate(top20):
    plt.scatter(peak_week[disease], [idx], color='red', s=100, label='Primary' if idx==0 else "")
    if secondary_peaks[disease]:
        plt.scatter(secondary_peaks[disease], [idx]*len(secondary_peaks[disease]), color='blue', s=50, label='Secondary' if idx==0 else "")

plt.yticks(range(len(top20)), top20)
plt.xlabel("ISO Week")
plt.title("Peak Weeks (Primary Red, Secondary Blue)  Top 20 Diseases")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(alpha=0.3)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Seasonality Strength Bar Chart
strength_order = ["Strong", "Moderate", "Weak", "None"]
strength_counts = seasonality_strength.value_counts().reindex(strength_order, fill_value=0)

plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.bar(strength_counts.index, strength_counts.values, color='skyblue')
plt.ylabel("Number of Diseases")
plt.title("Seasonality Strength Across Top 20 Diseases")
plt.grid(axis='y', alpha=0.2)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The following calculations are used:

  • Median Seasonal Curve - For each disease, the median weekly case count is calculated across all available years for each ISO week (weeks 153). This shows the "typical" weekly pattern to reduces outlier influence
  • Smoothing - A rolling average applied to the median seasonal curve to reduce short-term fluctuations or noise" so that peaks can easily be detected visually.
  • Primary Peak - Highest weekly value in a year.
  • Secondary Peak - Some diseases may have more than one seasonal peak (bimodal or multimodal patterns).
  • Seasonality Strength - Measures how strongly seasonal a disease is. This can help in prioritizing and planning actions/interventions.

Interpretation:

  • Primary peaks range from ISO week 1 (Invasive pneumococcal disease) to week 48 (Coccidioidomycosis groups), indicating that different pathogens follow very different seasonal cycles.
  • Several diseases exhibit multiple secondary peaks, suggesting complex multi-season transmission cycles (i.e. Chlamydia trachomatis, Hepatitis B/C chronic, Pertussis). These patterns indicate several periods of elevated activity, requiring ongoing monitoring throughout the year.
  • Some diseases show clean, single-season behavior with no secondary peaks (such as Salmonellosis, STEC, Cryptosporidiosis). These pathogens follow a strong and predictable annual seasonality curve.
  • Strong seasonality for Cryptosporidiosis during late-summer(week 34) and Coccidioidomycosis during winter (week 5).

Actionable Insights:

  • Targeted interventions should be done during peak weeks such as conducting vaccination, awareness campaigns, and testing for diseases with strong/moderate seasonality 12 weeks before peak weeks.
  • Year-Round Surveillance for Weakly Seasonal Diseases. Continuous monitoring and public education are necessary throughout the year.
  • Resource Allocation Based on Seasonality Strength: Strongly seasonal diseases surge staffing during peak weeks, minimal off-season. Weakly seasonal maintain consistent baseline resources year-round.
  • For diseases with multiple secondary peaks, multiple interventions may be required per year.

# ==========================================
# Analysis 5: Flag Analysis
# ==========================================

from IPython.display import display

# Identify date column
df_raw.columns = df_raw.columns.str.strip()

if 'Current MMWR Year' in df_raw.columns and 'MMWR WEEK' in df_raw.columns:
    df_raw['date'] = pd.to_datetime(
        df_raw['Current MMWR Year'].astype(str) + '-W' + df_raw['MMWR WEEK'].astype(str) + '-1',
        format='%Y-W%W-%w'
    )
else:
    raise ValueError("Year or Week column missing for date conversion.")

# Identify flag columns
flag_cols = [c for c in df_raw.columns if 'flag' in c.lower()]
if not flag_cols:
    print(" No flag columns detected.")
else:
    print(f"Detected flag columns: {flag_cols}\n")

    # Aggregate flags by Label + date
    agg_flag = (
        df_raw.groupby(['Label', 'date'], as_index=False)[flag_cols]
              .agg(lambda x: x.mode()[0] if not x.mode().empty else None)  # most common flag
    )

    df_flags = pd.merge(
        agg[['Label', 'date']],  # your cleaned weekly dataset
        agg_flag,
        on=['Label', 'date'],
        how='left'
    )

# Summary table for flag columns
    flag_summary = []
    for f in flag_cols:
        counts = df_flags[f].value_counts(dropna=False)
        pct = df_flags[f].value_counts(normalize=True, dropna=False) * 100
        summary = pd.DataFrame({
            'Flag Value': counts.index,
            'Count': counts.values,
            'Percentage': pct.values.round(2),
            'Column': f
        })
        summary['Rare Flag'] = summary['Percentage'] < 5
        flag_summary.append(summary)

# Output table
    flag_summary_df = pd.concat(flag_summary, ignore_index=True)
    display(flag_summary_df.sort_values(['Column','Percentage'], ascending=[True, False]))

Actionable Insights:

  • Consider filtering, imputing, or separately analyzing rows with provisional/missing flags (NaN, N, NP, NN) to avoid bias in cumulative counts or trends.

  • Maintain flag monitoring as part of routine data quality checks, especially when updating dashboards, visualizations, or forecasting models.

  3. Seasonality & Peak Weeks - Strong seasonality in Cryptosporidiosis and Coccidioidomycosis; moderate in foodborne diseases; weak in STIs. Primary and secondary peaks are identifiable, enabling precise timing for interventions.
  4. Geospatial Contribution - Top-contributing states are California, Florida, New York, Pennsylvania, and Virginia; top 10 states account for >60% of weekly cases.
  5. Data Quality & Flag Analysis - Most rows are reliable, but small proportions of provisional/missing flags exist (~11.5%). Communicate data limitations clearly to stakeholders.

Skills/Techiques Used

  1. Data Handling & Preprocessing
  • Cleaning and aggregating weekly-level CDC NNDSS data.
  • Feature engineering for analysis.
  • Handling missing data and maintaining data consistency across multiple aggregation levels.
  1. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
  • National and state-level disease trends.
  • Year-to-year and monthly cumulative comparisons.
  • Detection of outliers, anomalies, and rare events.
  1. Time-Series Analysis
  • Year-to-date cumulative comparisons (YTD vs previous year).
  • Monthly trend analysis for magnitude comparison.
  • Seasonal pattern detection using median seasonal curves.
  1. Seasonality & Peak Detection
  • Identifying primary and secondary peak weeks.
  • Calculating seasonality strength and classifying diseases (weak, moderate, strong).
  • Using rolling averages and peak-finding algorithms for signal smoothing and peak detection.
  1. Geospatial Analysis
  • Mapping disease contribution by state using choropleth and bar charts.
  • Interpreting high-burden regions for public health decision-making.
  1. Data Quality & Flag Analysis
  • Detecting provisional, missing, or special-handling data via flag columns.
  • Summarizing, quantifying, and interpreting impact on trend analysis.
  1. Visualization & Reporting
  • Multi-faceted visualization: bar charts, line plots, seasonal curves, choropleth maps.
  • Combining visual insights with summary tables for actionable interpretation.
  • Clear communication of analytical findings with practical recommendations.
  1. Analytical & Critical Thinking
  • Translating raw data into actionable insights for disease surveillance and public health planning.
  • Integrating multiple analyses (temporal, spatial, seasonal) to form a cohesive story.
